ORGANISATIONS responsible for importing the contaminated Premium Motor Spirit (PMS), should take responsibility and seek restitution for the national mishap. This was contained in a statement by the Nigerian Union of Journalists (national) titled: ‘PMS Methanol issue too sensitive to be politicized,’ which was signed by its president, Chris Isiguzo. Noting that the country has enjoyed uninterrupted availability of Premium Motor Spirit (PMS) over the last four years, Isiguzo stated that “The present challenge, the Union understands, is a result of the importation of PMS with higher than normal methanol level. Since the unfortunate development, it is regrettable to observe that there have been some blame game between the Nigeria National Petroleum Corporation, NNPC, and some of its designated importers over the ‘bad fuel’.”   Aisha Buhari took Kaduna-Abuja train back home for good…     Buhari’s Executive Order 10 unconstitutional, Supreme Court…     Deregistration of parties: Supreme Court fixes hearing for…   Read Also: Scarcity: Fuel supply improving in Lagos He said there should be a limit to the politicising of such a sensitive matter, especially with the measures already undertaken by the management of the NNPC and the presidential inquest on the way. - Advertisement - He stressed that focus should be on the conclusiveness of the probe panel as ordered by President Muhammadu Buhari, while adequate compensation should be paid to all verifiable claims of those whose vehicles may have been affected by the high methanol PMS. Isiguzo enjoined the NNPC through the Midstream and Downstream Regulatory Authority to monitor filling stations to ensure that those with products dispense them and not cause artificial scarcity.